input:
WIBTA for not giving Nick's sister a share of Nick's inheritance - to give to her daughters? | Nick's father died last year. Beforehand he showed Nick the final copy of his will - it was simple, 50% to Nick, 50% to Nick's half-sister.  

&nbsp;  

Nick wasn't always close with his Dad (parents split when Nick was young) and as a result Nick has never been close with his half-sister. She's much older than Nick, they've never lived together and until last summer they hadn't seen each other in 10 years. She has two daughters, one of whom Nick has never met. At this meeting, she did mention she'd *hoped* Dad would give something specifically to her daughters, but Nick shrugged this off as he knew he hadn't and Nick assumed she must not have seen the will.  

&nbsp;  

A few months later and upon sorting the estate, Nick is waiting for her to send Nick some documents, including the will, to sign. Nick messages to ask if she's received them yet and if she can forward them to Nick. This message is the reply Nick gets;  

&nbsp;  

'*I need to talk to you - Dad did want to leave something to the girls but was too ill to sort!*'  

&nbsp;  

Again, when shown the will and multiple times discussing it with him later, Nick's Dad didn't once say he'd wanted to change anything. Asking for clarification, in genuinely as calm a tone as Nick writes this post, stating that he'd been through the will with Nick beforehand, Nick simply asks what exactly Dad said he wanted to change? From seemingly nowhere Nick then receives this exact response;  

&nbsp;  

'*Hang on! What's your problem with this? I don't want the money it would go straight into the girls account. I'm surprise you are even doubting it!!!! Think about it, Dad loved my girls and wanted them look after. I spent a lot more time with dad so had more opportunities to discuss this. He even had their bank details in the care home but I could ask him to call the bank as he was too ill and too tired. Fucking hell, are you for real?!*'  

&nbsp;  

Asking her to calm down, stating all Nick ever did was ask what Dad said and how much he'd wanted to give to them, Nick eventually gets clarification that they never discussed specifics - 'he just said he wanted them looked after'. Happy to provide his messages word for word in the comments if need be, Nick is just aware of going over the character limit here.  

&nbsp;  

Despite not being close with them and not having even met both daughters, as someone with no children of his own, Nick had previously considered offering some of the money as extra to them. But due to being largely kept out of the loop of funeral organisation and in the end only being told about the burial of the ashes literally less than 48 hours beforehand, Nick realised as they really aren't close, that's not his concern and if that's what Dad *really* wanted, he'd have included it in the will in the first place. This latest exchange just cements that feeling.  

&nbsp;  

Would Nick be the asshole for this? Again, they're not close and Nick can tell you with certainty that once this is over, they'll go back to rarely speaking to each other - but they are technically his nieces.
